And they do make money by allowing non-subscribed end-users to download articles for a fee. OA is a complicated subject, I get that. But try to understand what academic libraries are going through when it comes to journal access. There are reasons why so many of us are pro-OA.

In the end, you're the only one who can decide which option is best for you but know that, w/ subscription journals, your work is often locked behind a paywall for however long that journal wants to keep it and make money off of it.

Some of the more popular journals can run into the $1000s for a year of online-only access, no print copies. So yes, APCs can suck, but it doesn't make an OA journal predatory. They're trying to survive and disseminate  information. There are pros and cons on both sides.

These costs might be written into tuition or library fees but it's absolutely being paid by someone. All those journals you access "for free" aren't free, which is why your institutions have to pick and choose what they'll subscribe too.

Saw a post about OA journals and Author Publishing Fees and what a problem this is. Someone commented that, w/ subscription journals, "nobody pays" and y'all, that is NOT true. Your institution is paying the exorbitant subscription fees. You're paying, you just don't realize it.
